04467nam a22006615i 9780226358338DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015045699  a9780226358338  a(DE-B1597)524320  a(OCoLC)956376016  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH78b.H45 2016 4aQH78b.H45 2017 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a576.842231 aHeise, Ursula K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagining Extinction :bThe Cultural Meanings of Endangered Species /cUrsula K. Heise. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b2 color plates, 13 halftones, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: From the End of Nature to the Beginning of the Anthropocene -- t1. Lost Dogs, Last Birds, and Listed Species: Elegy and Comedy in Conservation Stories -- t2. From Arks to ARKive.org: Database, Epic, and Biodiversity -- t3. The Legal Lives of Endangered Species: Biodiversity Laws and Culture -- t4. Mass Extinction and Mass Slaughter: Biodiversity, Violence, and the Dangers of Domestication -- t5. Biodiversity, Environmental Justice, and Multispecies Communities -- t6. Multispecies Fictions for the Anthropocene -- tCoda: The Hug of the Polar Bear -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are currently facing the sixth mass extinction of species in the history of life on Earth, biologists claim—the first one caused by humans. Activists, filmmakers, writers, and artists are seeking to bring the crisis to the public’s attention through stories and images that use the strategies of elegy, tragedy, epic, and even comedy. Imagining Extinction is the first book to examine the cultural frameworks shaping these narratives and images. Ursula K. Heise argues that understanding these stories and symbols is indispensable for any effective advocacy on behalf of endangered species. More than that, she shows how biodiversity conservation, even and especially in its scientific and legal dimensions, is shaped by cultural assumptions about what is valuable in nature and what is not. These assumptions are hardwired into even seemingly neutral tools such as biodiversity databases and laws for the protection of endangered species. Heise shows that the conflicts and convergences of biodiversity conservation with animal welfare advocacy, environmental justice, and discussions about the Anthropocene open up a new vision of multispecies justice. Ultimately, Imagining Extinction demonstrates that biodiversity, endangered species, and extinction are not only scientific questions but issues of histories, cultures, and values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEndangered species. 0aExtinct animals. 0aExtinction (Biology) 0aExtinction (Biology). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  abiodiversity conservation.  acosmopolitanism.  aecocriticism.  aendangered species.  aenvironmental humanities.  aenvironmental justice.  aenvironmental narrative.  aextinction.  amultispecies theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226358338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226358338/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles